'''Headworks''' is a civil engineering term for any structure at the head or diversion point of a waterway. It is smaller than a [[barrage (dam)|barrage]] and is used to divert water from a river into a canal or from a large canal into a smaller canal.<ref>{{cite book |title=Manual of irrigation engineering|first1=Herbert Michael |last1=Wilson|chapter=CHAPTER 10. HEADWORKS AND DIVERSION WEIRS |url=https://archive.org/details/manualirrigatio02wilsgoog |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|year=1896|isbn= |page=155  |ref= }} at [[Web archive]]</ref>

Historically the phrase "headworks" derives from the traditional approach of diverting water at the start of an irrigation network and the location of these processes at the "head of the works".

